summaries.title: Balancing Research and Cultural Expectations
summaries.summaryText: Priya balanced heavy research commitments with cultural obligations, feeling pressure to excel as a first-gen Indian-American student in tech. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Family Support and Pressure as a Dual Motivation
summaries.summaryText: As a first-generation student, Daniels parents provided emotional encouragement but limited academic guidance. Their sacrifices motivated him, though he expressed anxiety about failing to meet expectations. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Navigating Gender Bias in Research Environments
summaries.summaryText: She recounted experiences where her technical contributions were overlooked and strategies she used to assert confidence. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Family Support and Pressure as a Dual Motivation
summaries.summaryText: As a first-generation student, Daniels parents provided emotional encouragement but limited academic guidance. Their sacrifices motivated him, though he expressed anxiety about failing to meet expectations. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Academic Rigor with Limited Peer Representation
summaries.summaryText: Maria described feeling academically capable but often isolated in her computer engineering courses, where few other Latina students were enrolled. She mentioned that faculty were supportive when approached, but that representation and group belonging remained low, especially during first-year lab sections. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Microaggressions and Invisible Labor in Group Dynamics
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah recounted repeated experiences of having her technical input questioned in group settings. She also described taking on emotional labor to support other students facing similar bias. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Integrating Mental Health Advocacy with STEM Identity
summaries.summaryText: Sarah described bridging mental health awareness into STEM culture through peer-led workshops. [Part 3/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Joined the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers during her first semester to find community and mentorship. [Timeline 1]
Faced subtle exclusion in a group design project where her ideas were initially dismissed. [Timeline 4]
Faced academic probation warning after struggling with Calculus II due to lack of tutoring access. [Timeline 1]
Served as a teaching assistant for an introductory design course, emphasizing peer inclusivity. [Timeline 4]
Presented research poster at a regional engineering conference, receiving recognition from faculty mentors. [Timeline 1]
Struggled during his first programming course, leading him to seek help from tutoring and peers. [Timeline 1]
Co-founded a mentorship initiative within NSBE for first- and second-year engineering students. [Timeline 3]
Presented senior capstone project on sustainable urban drainage systems, earning department recognition. [Timeline 3]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Marias sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniels experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Family Expectations and Cultural Motivation
themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyahs mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniels experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Peer Mentorship as a Belonging Intervention
themes.description: Daniel emphasized how structured mentorship programs provided psychological safety and belonging cues, normalizing struggle and improving persistence among marginalized students. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Marias sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Intersection of Culture and Academic Identity
themes.description: Cultural expectations of excellence create dual pressure for first-gen students in technical majors. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyahs experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Marias reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 2]

themes.title: First-Generation Adaptation to STEM Rigor
themes.description: Luiss story demonstrates resilience through peer and cultural support. [Extended 1]

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here  sharing what weve learned keeps us going when the system doesnt always see us. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Aaliyah on the value of mentorship networks.

quotes.quoteText: My parents always say 'you represent the family'it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Priya describing family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: No one in my family went to college, so I didnt even know how office hours worked my first semester. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Maria describing her initial confusion with academic expectations as a first-gen student.

quotes.quoteText: You cant innovate if youre burned out  STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Sarah connecting wellness and academic productivity.

quotes.quoteText: At first I thought I wasnt smart enough, but then I realized everyones struggling; we just dont talk about it. [Context 2]

quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethans reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Create summer bridge programs for high school students
Offer needs-based scholarships for pre-college engineering camps

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Create service-learning credit for mentorship and advocacy roles
Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethans reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 4]
